      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "From a libertarian viewpoint, any mandate—even a \"moderate\" one—is a form of state coercion because it compels individuals to conform their speech to a predefined standard. Philosophers like Robert Nozick argue that individuals have absolute rights over their own actions and expression, and the state infringing on that sphere, even for perceived public good, constitutes a violation of self-ownership. Therefore, requiring age verification or content filtering is seen as the government dictating the boundaries of private thought, which is a fundamental assault on autonomy.",
      "source": "target",
